<dl id="n34008a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34008a">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34008a"> 8(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> logothete <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n34008a"><li>FW 156.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fc/lexfc.htm#n34008a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fc/l39fc.htm#n34008a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n34008a">MS Yale 9.3-*7a</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:217 <a name="fcd6" href="../../ff/fdra/fda.htm#fcd6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fc/fcd6.htm#n34008a">Draft: I.6&sect;3.6</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The patriarch has the assistance and support of a large household, a survival from Byzantine times. Amongst them, actually or potentially, are the grand steward &hellip; who serves his as deacon in the liturgy and presents candidates for orders; the grand visitor &hellip;, who superintends the monasteries; the sacristan &hellip;; the chancellor &hellip; who superintends ecclesiastical causes; the deputy-visitor &hellip;, who visits the nunneries; the protonotary &hellip;; <mark>the logothete</mark> &hellip;, a most important lay officer, who represents the patriarch at the Porte and elsewhere outside, the censer-bearer &hellip;, who seems to be also a kind of captain of the guard &hellip;; the referendary &hellip;; the secretary &hellip;; the chief syndic &hellip;, who is a judge of lesser causes; the recorder &hellip;; and so on down to the cleaner of the lamps &hellip;, the attendant of the lights &hellip;, and the bearer of the images &hellip; and of the holy ointment &hellip;. <small> &ldquo;ORTHODOX EASTERN CHURCH&rdquo; <a name="EBOEC" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBOEC"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 337 [The Four Ancient Patriarchates]</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Entry transferred to text block on <a name="n34028a" href="n34all.htm#n34028a">N34 (VI.B.27):028(a)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
